{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":27184,"name":"","username":"esakylli","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/esakylli/{size}/887_2.png","created_at":"2019-01-04T11:12:37.259Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eI have an issue with bullet physics when using triangle mesh as the collision shape.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eMy scenario is this:\u003cbr\u003e\nI have a static physics body on a node, and set the collision shape for it to triangle mesh (because I have created a custom geometry).\u003cbr\u003e\nOn top of that body I have a dynamic body, with a collision shape of box.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWhen the simulation is started the dynamic box moves up a little. In the debug view of the physics world I can see that there is a small gap between the static body and the dynamic body.\u003cbr\u003e\nBut the debug view seems to be showing the shapes correctly.\u003cbr\u003e\nIf I apply some force to the dynamic body it behaves very strange, jittering on top of the static body.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eEven if I don‚Äôt use my custom geometry, instead use the ordinary Box.mdl with triangle mesh as the shape I get the same strange behaviour.\u003cbr\u003e\nIf I use a convex hull for the static body, I see the little gap between the bodies but I don‚Äôt get the strange jittering.\u003cbr\u003e\nIf I change the static body to a box, then all is fine.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAnyone have any clue of what‚Äôs going on here?\u003cbr\u003e\nBtw, I‚Äôm using UrhoSharp (but I don‚Äôt think it should matter).\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2019-01-04T11:12:37.259Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":330,"reads":27,"readers_count":26,"score":1655.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":4793,"topic_slug":"bullet-physics-triangle-mesh","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":647,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":27187,"name":"","username":"esakylli","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/esakylli/{size}/887_2.png","created_at":"2019-01-04T15:02:31.415Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eI found a solution to my problem:\u003cbr\u003e\nBy setting margin to 0 on the static collision shape it works as expected.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBut I don‚Äôt know why this is the case‚Ä¶ I saw in the source code that default is 0.04 for all shape types.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2019-01-12T12:26:49.918Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":6,"reads":24,"readers_count":23,"score":39.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":4793,"topic_slug":"bullet-physics-triangle-mesh","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":647,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":true},{"id":27188,"name":"Justin Miller","username":"jmiller","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/jmiller/{size}/2367_2.png","created_at":"2019-01-04T16:20:11.627Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003ePresumably, Collision Margin 0.04 was thought a reasonable generic default. ‚ÄòIdeal‚Äô values currently depend at least on shape type and \u003ca h